-- Ellies Holdings, Pick n Pay May Move: South African Equity Market Preview
-- Garth Theunissen
-- 2010-07-16T05:37:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-16/ellies-holdings-pick-n-pay-may-move-south-african-equity-market-preview.html

          
          
             The following stocks may rise or
fall in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last close.  
 The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  gained 31.01, or 0.1
percent, to 27,474.68 in Johannesburg.  
 Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ): Copper fell for a second day,
losing as much as 0.5 percent to $6,650 a metric ton on the
London Metal Exchange. Stock of Anglo, the diversified mining
company that makes up almost 10 percent of South Africa’s
benchmark stock index, fell 2.35 rand, or 0.9 percent, to 274.65
rand. Shares in larger rival  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ) dropped
98 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 210.96 rand.  
 Dimension Data Plc  (DDT SJ): The technology-services
company hasn’t spoken to other companies that could launch a
takeover bid following yesterday’s announcement that Japan’s
Nippon Telegraph & Telephone Corp. would acquire Dimension Data
for $3.2 billion, Chairman  Jeremy Ord  said in an interview with
702 Talk Radio late yesterday. Dimension Data’s stock climbed
2.55 rand, or 22 percent, to 14.12 rand, its biggest advance in
more than seven years.  
 Ellies Holdings Ltd.  (ELI SJ): The manufacturer of
satellite-television equipment said it ended talks to buy Power
Line Africa (Pty) Ltd. The shares were unchanged at 1.63 rand.  
 Pick n Pay Stores Ltd.  (PIK SJ): South Africa’s second-
largest food retailer said Chief Financial Officer  Dennis Cope ,
who is due to retire in April next year, sold shares in the
company worth 8.7 million rand ($1.15 million). Pick n Pay rose
31 cents, or 0.7 percent, to 44.01 rand.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ): Crude oil for August delivery slipped
as much as 0.3 percent to $76.37 a barrel in electronic trading
in New York. Stock of Sasol, the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, fell 35 cents, or 0.1 percent, to 286 rand.  
 Shares or American depositary receipts of the following
South African companies closed as follows:  
 Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) added 0.2 percent to $18.34.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) slid 0.2 percent to $41.34. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) rose 1.1 percent to $56.75. DRDGold Ltd.
(DROOY US) fell 0.7 percent to $4.26. Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI US)
gained 1.1 percent to $13.44. Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HMY US)
fell 0.4 percent to $10.71. Impala Platinum Holdings Co. (IMPUY
US) climbed 0.7 percent to $24.80. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US) was
unchanged at $4.38. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) fell 0.4 percent to
$37.69. Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TLKGY US) slumped 8.8 percent
to $18.  
